Appendix C: Fokker‑Planck Formulation and Stochastic Analysis

C.1 Derivation of the Fokker‑Planck Equation for Optical Depth

The optical depth SDE is:

d\tau_t = a(\tau_t, u_t) dt + \sigma_\tau dW_t,

where a(\tau, u) = \Phi_d \sigma_{\text{ext}} - R_{\text{clean}}(u). The corresponding Fokker‑Planck equation for the probability density p(\tau, t) is:

\frac{\partial p}{\partial t} = -\frac{\partial}{\partial \tau} \left( a(\tau, u) p \right) + \frac{1}{2} \sigma_\tau^2 \frac{\partial^2 p}{\partial \tau^2}.

The steady-state distribution p_{\text{ss}}(\tau) satisfies:

\frac{d}{d\tau} \left( a(\tau, u) p_{\text{ss}} \right) = \frac{1}{2} \sigma_\tau^2 \frac{d^2 p_{\text{ss}}}{d\tau^2}.

Integrating once:

a(\tau, u) p_{\text{ss}} - \frac{1}{2} \sigma_\tau^2 \frac{d p_{\text{ss}}}{d\tau} = J,

where J is the constant probability current. For reflecting boundaries or a potential well, J=0. Then:

\frac{d p_{\text{ss}}}{d\tau} = \frac{2 a(\tau, u)}{\sigma_\tau^2} p_{\text{ss}} \quad \Rightarrow \quad p_{\text{ss}}(\tau) = C \exp\left( \int_0^\tau \frac{2 a(\tau', u)}{\sigma_\tau^2} d\tau' \right).

This allows the CMDP to optimize the expected value \mathbb{E}[\tau] = \int \tau p_{\text{ss}}(\tau) d\tau rather than just the instantaneous value.

