Appendix D: PINN Convergence and Regularization Theory

D.1 Detailed Proof of Theorem 2 (Well‑Posedness)

Theorem 2. For the inverse problem I_{\text{meas}} = \mathcal{F}(\tau) + \epsilon with \mathcal{F}(\tau) = I_0 e^{-\tau} (single-scattering approximation), the PINN loss \mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\theta}) with Tikhonov regularization \beta_2 \|\nabla \tau\|_2^2 has a unique minimizer in H^1(\mathcal{S}) as \epsilon \to 0 and M \to \infty.

Proof. The forward operator \mathcal{F}: L^\infty(\mathcal{S}) \to L^2(\mathcal{S}) is continuous and injective because the exponential function is strictly monotonic. The inverse problem is ill‑posed due to compactness of \mathcal{F}. Regularization via the Sobolev norm \|\tau\|_{H^1}^2 = \|\tau\|_2^2 + \|\nabla \tau\|_2^2 yields the Tikhonov functional:

J_\alpha(\tau) = \|\mathcal{F}(\tau) - I_{\text{meas}}\|_2^2 + \alpha \|\tau\|_{H^1}^2.

For \alpha > 0, J_\alpha is strictly convex and coercive, hence has a unique minimizer \tau_\alpha. As \alpha \to 0 and noise level \delta \to 0 with \alpha(\delta) \to 0 appropriately, \tau_\alpha converges to the true solution. The PINN architecture with sufficient width can approximate any H^1 function arbitrarily well (universal approximation theorem for Sobolev spaces). The training with gradient descent on empirical risk yields the minimizer in the limit of infinite data. ∎

D.2 Lemma 5 (PINN Residual Convergence) – Expanded Proof

Lemma 5. If \mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\theta}) < \epsilon, then \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}\|_2 < \sqrt{\epsilon/\beta_1}.

Proof. By definition, \mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\theta}) = \|I_{\text{pred}} - I_{\text{meas}}\|_2^2 + \beta_1 \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}\|_2^2 + \beta_2 \|\nabla \cdot \mathbf{J} + \partial_t n\|_2^2 \ge \beta_1 \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}\|_2^2. Hence \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}\|_2^2 \le \mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{\theta})/\beta_1 < \epsilon/\beta_1. Taking square roots gives the bound. As \epsilon \to 0, the residual vanishes in L^2, implying that I_{\text{pred}} satisfies the RTE in the weak sense. ∎

