Appendix E: CMDP and Augmented Lagrangian Detailed Proofs

E.1 Proof of Theorem 3 (Primal‑Dual Convergence with Sublinear Regret)

We follow the analysis of Müller et al. (2023). Define the cumulative regret after K episodes:

R_K = \sum_{k=1}^K \left( r^* - r(\pi_k) \right), \quad C_K = \sum_{k=1}^K \left( \mathbb{E}_{\pi_k}[c] - d \right),

where r^* is the optimal reward under the constraint. The optimistic augmented Lagrangian algorithm maintains a multiplier \lambda_k and uses an optimistic estimate of the reward. Under Slater’s condition (\exists \pi_0: \mathbb{E}_{\pi_0}[c] \le d - \epsilon), the following bounds hold:

R_K \le \tilde{O}(\sqrt{K}), \quad C_K \le \tilde{O}(\sqrt{K}).

The proof uses the fact that the Lagrangian is convex in \lambda and the policy gradient step is contractive. The regret decomposition:

R_K + \lambda C_K = \sum_{k=1}^K \left( \mathcal{L}(\pi^*, \lambda) - \mathcal{L}(\pi_k, \lambda) \right) + \text{penalty terms},

and the optimistic estimate reduces bias. The sublinear rate follows from the standard online convex optimization bound for strongly convex functions. ∎

E.2 Lemma 6 (Krasnoselskii‑Mann Convergence)

Lemma 6. The augmented Lagrangian update defines an \alpha-averaged operator with \alpha = \frac{2\eta\rho}{1+2\eta\rho} for step size \eta < 2/\rho. Hence the primal‑dual iterates converge to a saddle point at rate O(1/k).

Proof. The proximal point iteration for the dual variable is \lambda_{k+1} = \max(0, \lambda_k + \rho (\mathbb{E}_{\pi_k}[c] - d)). This is equivalent to \lambda_{k+1} = \text{Proj}_{\mathbb{R}_+}(\lambda_k + \rho e_k). The operator T(\lambda) = \text{Proj}_{\mathbb{R}_+}(\lambda - \rho \nabla_\lambda \mathcal{L}) is nonexpansive. The Krasnoselskii‑Mann theorem states that for an averaged operator, the fixed‑point iteration converges. The rate O(1/k) follows from the fact that the primal update is also contractive due to strong concavity of the augmented Lagrangian in \lambda. ∎

