Appendix I: Detailed Continuity Equation for Dust Measure

I.1 Derivation of Weak Form

Let \mu_t be the measure representing dust distribution. For any test function \varphi \in C_c^\infty(\mathcal{X}), the weak form of the continuity equation is:

\frac{d}{dt} \int_{\mathcal{X}} \varphi \, d\mu_t = \int_{\mathcal{X}} \left( \mathbf{v} \cdot \nabla_x \varphi + \frac{\partial \varphi}{\partial R} \dot{R} + \frac{\partial \varphi}{\partial q} \dot{q} \right) d\mu_t + \int_{\mathcal{X}} \varphi \, d(\mathcal{S} - \mathcal{R}).

This follows from integration by parts and the fact that the flux term \nabla \cdot (\mathbf{v} \mu_t) in distributional sense yields the first term. The deposition \mathcal{S} is a Poisson point process with rate \lambda_{\text{dep}}, while removal \mathcal{R} is proportional to the field strength. The existence of a unique solution follows from the theory of measure‑valued stochastic differential equations (see, e.g., Dawson’s superprocess).

